here Panos from N Software Patents. Yeah so hi everyone I am Panos Algropoulos. I have

00:54.160 --> 01:00.640
been working on the N Software Patents campaign for a while for about two years approximately.

01:00.640 --> 01:06.160
Just to give an overview of the presentation today I am going to talk about in general

01:06.160 --> 01:13.440
what's the deal with SAPs and FRAND and a rough overview of case law and then Kiaran

01:13.440 --> 01:18.720
will present the free software's toughest problem and five fixes we can think about

01:18.720 --> 01:28.640
it. So what's the deal with SAPs and FRAND? Two words that are probably unknown to many.

01:28.640 --> 01:35.840
SAP stands for Standard Essential Patent and FRAND stands for Fair, Reasonable and

01:35.840 --> 01:45.720
Non-Discriminatory. Just to illustrate what's going on here. As we all know that in technology

01:45.720 --> 01:54.080
standards are very important so if we want devices to work with each other and we want

01:54.080 --> 02:04.320
them to be incompatible we need to use a standard right. So these standards are usually the

02:04.320 --> 02:09.780
rules for these standards are going to be set up by standard setting organizations.

02:09.780 --> 02:17.800
So what happens is that for a known standard there are usually patents that are very important

02:17.800 --> 02:26.360
for the standard to work. So those standards are called standard essential patents and

02:26.360 --> 02:33.240
if one wants to participate in the standard they need to use the patent so that person

02:33.240 --> 02:40.560
is called implementer and they have to get a license from the SAP holder. Now of course

02:40.560 --> 02:47.880
as we all know a patent is very restrictive to everyone so here's what standard setting

02:47.880 --> 02:54.960
organizations do. They require from the SAP holders to license their patents their SAPs

02:54.960 --> 03:05.960
under FRAND licenses. Now it sounds great but there are issues. As we said FRAND stands

03:05.960 --> 03:14.800
for Fair, Reasonable and Non-Discriminatory but that's a very very very vague term. First

03:14.800 --> 03:21.360
of all it can affect everyone that's working with standards and that includes network protocols,

03:21.360 --> 03:29.560
Internet of Things, audio video codecs, the automotive industry and so on and on. The

03:29.560 --> 03:40.240
problem is that when the implementers have to use the patents they have to come under

03:40.240 --> 03:49.480
agreements with the SAP holders and the SAP holders they try to charge as much money as

03:49.480 --> 03:57.920
possible and most likely the implementers are not very satisfied with that. So the real

03:57.920 --> 04:03.000
problem is that there's a potential abuse of dominant power, of dominant position by

04:03.000 --> 04:08.560
the SAP holders and the high transaction costs for implementers are simply unsustainable

04:08.560 --> 04:18.440
for SMEs, for small and medium enterprises. And that in general adds up to the legal uncertainty

04:18.440 --> 04:31.760
regarding software patents. So to be more specific on the way this has been reflected

04:31.760 --> 04:36.400
in the courts because what happens is that when you have an implementer and they come

04:36.400 --> 04:44.200
into a disagreement with a patent holder what happens is that litigation happens. So they

04:44.200 --> 04:52.760
go to the courts and what do the courts say? Well they should try to help as much as possible.

04:52.760 --> 05:00.080
I have a layout here of the courts, of the court decisions that have been relevant and

05:00.080 --> 05:05.240
have been basically the landmark decisions in Europe. First of all it all started with

05:05.240 --> 05:12.760
the German Federal Supreme Court and it started with a very strict and conservative stance

05:12.760 --> 05:22.200
very pro-ACP holder stance because it basically had a very strict test for a front defence

05:22.200 --> 05:29.800
and the front defence is basically when the implementer says yes you are the SAP holder

05:29.800 --> 05:35.960
but the money that you charge for that are way too high for me to actually participate

05:35.960 --> 05:43.320
in the market and that is an abuse of your dominant position. And the German Federal

05:43.320 --> 05:53.280
Supreme Court was more in favour of the patent holders and that was in 2009. But then what

05:53.280 --> 06:01.080
happened is that we had a very important decision from the European Court of Justice that concerned

06:01.080 --> 06:08.600
competition law and it took a more balanced approach. And then in 2020 there was another

06:08.600 --> 06:18.120
decision, actually there was no decision, there was a German lower court which asked

06:18.120 --> 06:25.720
for more clarifications from the European Court of Justice and unfortunately for everyone

06:25.720 --> 06:34.280
the decision was, there was no decision, it was settled out of court so the court had

06:34.280 --> 06:43.080
no chance to answer those questions. To be more specific on what the German Federal Supreme

06:43.080 --> 06:53.640
Court said back in 2009, it had a very strict test and it said the alleged infringer can

06:53.640 --> 07:00.280
rely on a competition law defence only if it does the following two steps, only if it

07:00.280 --> 07:07.000
unconditionally offers to enter into a licence agreement with the SAP holder and more importantly

07:07.000 --> 07:13.280
if it behaves as if it were an actual licensee so that would mean that it would have to act

07:13.280 --> 07:19.920
as if there is already a licence and pay royalties and it was up to the defendant to prove that

07:19.920 --> 07:31.120
the conditions above are fulfilled. What happened though is that in 2014 there were two important

07:31.120 --> 07:38.120
commission decisions about anti-trust issues with Motorola and Samsung and the European

07:38.120 --> 07:44.720
Commission stated that a patent holder abuses its domain position when having given a front

07:44.720 --> 07:51.120
commitment over an SAP to a standard setting organisation, it seeks injunction against

07:51.120 --> 07:57.200
a willing licensee and a willing licensee remains free to challenge the validity of the

07:57.200 --> 08:04.080
patent or its infringement. That was very important because the German courts didn't

08:04.080 --> 08:13.280
recognise that, they didn't expect the defendant to give up some fundamental rights like this.

08:13.280 --> 08:28.120
So in about 2015 the European Court of Justice responded to a lower German court because

08:28.120 --> 08:34.160
the German courts recognised that there is a difference between what the German Federal

08:34.160 --> 08:39.920
Supreme Court says and what the European Commission is doing. So the European Court of Justice

08:39.920 --> 08:48.720
came in and clarified what's going on and it said there is a very broad test here but

08:48.720 --> 08:55.720
it's helpful enough for national courts to expand it further. The SAP holder must alert

08:55.720 --> 09:01.480
the implementer in writing of the infringement complaint of by noting the relevant SAP and

09:01.480 --> 09:08.440
how it shall is to be infringed. The implementer must express a willingness to conclude a licensing

09:08.440 --> 09:15.840
agreement on front terms. The SAP holder must provide a specific written offer for a licence

09:15.840 --> 09:21.720
on front terms. The implementer must diligently respond to that offer in accordance with recognised

09:21.720 --> 09:26.840
commercial practices and in good faith. And if the implementer does not accept the offer

09:26.840 --> 09:32.880
made to it, a counter offer that corresponds to front terms should be made. So based on

09:32.880 --> 09:40.280
that language you can probably figure out that the courts didn't really solve any problems.

09:40.280 --> 09:49.280
What they basically helped is to help the companies negotiate better on what front really

09:49.280 --> 09:58.720
is. And you might suggest from the name of the campaign and so forth the patents what

09:58.720 --> 10:05.160
we're trying to do. But it's important to follow decisions like this because it's important

10:05.160 --> 10:17.640
to understand how patents work and how front can actually affect standards. And finally

10:17.640 --> 10:23.280
just for good information there are more cases that should be studied but we don't have the

10:23.280 --> 10:29.520
time to represent them here. It's the United Kingdom Supreme Court Unwired, Planet versus

10:29.520 --> 10:37.560
Broadway in 2020 that concerns the UK. And there are two more decisions from the German

10:37.560 --> 10:46.200
Federal Supreme Court in 2020 that are also of great importance. So with that I conclude

10:46.200 --> 11:03.240
my presentation and I give the floor to Kia.

