12:23.800 --> 12:29.200
no it's got nothing to do with patents. So audio video patents are the worst case scenario

12:29.200 --> 12:35.680
for software because you have to form a standard first off. You then have to convince all of

12:35.680 --> 12:38.720
the manufacturers of hardware that this is worth putting into their hardware because

12:38.720 --> 12:44.160
you cannot do audio video with just software. Audio video software used to be optimised

12:44.160 --> 12:47.720
for decoding because encoding would happen on some mainframe somewhere and you'd download

12:47.720 --> 12:51.680
the video and you'd watch it. But now with video chat you have to do real time encoding,

12:51.680 --> 12:55.160
transmission so you need a small file size and then decoding and it should be almost

12:55.160 --> 13:00.640
real time. You convince these hardware manufacturers to put it onto their hardware and then you

13:00.640 --> 13:04.800
have to wait five years because then you have to wait for everyone, a whole world of computer

13:04.800 --> 13:08.280
users to throw out their current hardware and buy a new generation of hardware. So after

13:08.280 --> 13:12.400
five years finally the standard will be hardware accelerated on everyone's computer and then

13:12.400 --> 13:17.400
you can really use it. If at that point somebody comes along with a patent and says actually

13:17.400 --> 13:21.640
I own a bit of that software, there is very little you can do. You can no longer innovate

13:21.640 --> 13:27.680
around the problem. So software patents on standards are the worst type of patents for

13:27.680 --> 13:33.800
software and on video patent standards they are the worst of the worst. This is happening

13:33.800 --> 13:38.520
already. We have an audio format Opus which is not very famous however it is successor

13:38.520 --> 13:43.520
to the AUG audio format. It is used in a lot of hardware devices. There is currently a

13:43.520 --> 13:49.640
patent pool being formed to threaten the Opus audio format. We have the AV1 video format

13:49.640 --> 13:55.600
which is being developed to be freely implementable and already there has been a request sent

13:55.600 --> 13:59.320
to the European Commission to investigate the people working on this for anti-competitive

13:59.320 --> 14:04.520
practices because trying to help each other avoid patent problems might be a bad thing

14:04.520 --> 14:12.640
for some companies. Before I get into it I saw yesterday there was published a paper

14:12.640 --> 14:17.760
by Andrew Katz and four other researchers. I didn't get their names but it is on the

14:17.760 --> 14:22.240
implementing the HEVC standard in software so I expect that is very interesting but I

14:22.240 --> 14:27.480
will not be talking about it. There are a lot of topics here. So there was a commission

14:27.480 --> 14:32.360
call for input last year. There were responses from Open Forum Europe who I currently work

14:32.360 --> 14:39.800
for and from Open Source Initiative. However these comments were sent based on not actually

14:39.800 --> 14:44.120
knowing what text is going to be presented. So they were kind of general comments on what

14:44.120 --> 14:50.160
patent policy could be like. We still haven't seen the text that is going to be presented

14:50.160 --> 14:54.400
by the European Commission but as I said this is early stage planning for a campaign. We

14:54.400 --> 14:58.680
have to start thinking about what possibilities we have to fix this. What different form can

14:58.680 --> 15:02.520
it take? Because when we are talking about policy makers the way it works is you have

15:02.520 --> 15:07.840
to give them a list of different fixes that you are looking for and then they will say

15:07.840 --> 15:12.360
which ones are politically possible and then you have to start trying to maximise each

15:12.360 --> 15:17.360
of the ones that are politically possible. So I have found five starting ideas but this

15:17.360 --> 15:22.520
is a discussion document basically. We can discuss them further in the coming weeks.

15:22.520 --> 15:27.280
The first idea would be a carve out specific to free software. A few years ago this might

15:27.280 --> 15:31.800
have sounded a bit overly optimistic but now in the Cyber Resilience Act and the Product

15:31.800 --> 15:36.720
Liability Directive there is this text and when we first saw it we were amazed to see

15:36.720 --> 15:42.920
free and open source software should not be covered. Excellent. Of course once you start

15:42.920 --> 15:47.240
reading it then you realise well there is an objective limitation here. You can use

15:47.240 --> 15:53.040
this exemption if you are trying to do innovation or research. There is a commercial activity

15:53.040 --> 15:56.360
limitation and we all know that commercial activity has never been defined and is an

15:56.360 --> 16:01.680
endless source of clarity for what exactly that means for software and online activities

16:01.680 --> 16:07.280
and it should be exempted. So a judge will have to interpret whether or not you are allowed

16:07.280 --> 16:11.640
to use this exemption which basically means that nobody can confidently make use of this

16:11.640 --> 16:16.160
exemption so it is not very useful. However the fact that this is in a document from the

16:16.160 --> 16:20.840
Commission in two proposals for regulations tells us that inside the Commission something

16:20.840 --> 16:27.080
along these lines is acceptable. They didn't get the wording quite right at this time but

16:27.080 --> 16:31.480
they are not completely opposed to this kind of thing. So this is a starting point maybe

16:31.480 --> 16:38.720
we can do something along these lines. The second possibility would be a similar end

16:38.720 --> 16:43.320
result but from a different starting point and would be to try and carve industry into

16:43.320 --> 16:48.880
two sections. For example we might find that small and medium business in the manufacturing

16:48.880 --> 16:53.440
and pharmaceutical areas might be perfectly happy with having more patents and might want

16:53.440 --> 16:57.160
help from the Commission to apply for patents and use their patents. We happen to not like

16:57.160 --> 17:03.680
that so maybe we should have a different regime for them and one for us. There is already

17:03.680 --> 17:07.720
as part of this patent package there is a regulation that is specific to pharmaceutical

17:07.720 --> 17:13.600
patents so the Commission is not opposed to singling out sector by sector. Our argument

17:13.600 --> 17:19.480
can be that our sector is different because we have collaborative models and we have market

17:19.480 --> 17:24.440
solutions. If you look at the patent clauses of the GPL and the Apache 2.0 license we already

17:24.440 --> 17:28.920
have market solutions so maybe we can tell the European Commission don't interfere with

17:28.920 --> 17:37.680
what we are already fixing. A third fix and this is still quite early stage is the idea

17:37.680 --> 17:43.000
of competition law. I have always believed that there is not enough discussion of how

17:43.000 --> 17:47.960
competition law is weakened by the existence of patents. The European Commission loves

17:47.960 --> 17:51.760
to work on patent law and it is a big topic in the European Commission but it just seems

17:51.760 --> 17:56.520
that there is not enough dialogue between people who are enforcing competition law and

17:56.520 --> 18:02.160
people who are working on patent policy. So I think maybe if we could find a way to make

18:02.160 --> 18:07.440
it clearer to the European Commission and European institutions in general that how

18:07.440 --> 18:11.880
these two topics interact maybe we could help make them understand what we are trying to

18:11.880 --> 18:18.200
achieve. The fourth one, there are only five, I am not going to go on all night, the fourth

18:18.200 --> 18:22.240
one is something that we will definitely be discussed because the Commission has mentioned

18:22.240 --> 18:28.640
this in their documents. So Fran, at times we think the idea of non-discriminatory that

18:28.640 --> 18:33.800
must help us because we don't want regimes that discriminate against free software. We

18:33.800 --> 18:40.600
need patent regimes that allow for royalty free use of patents. However, non-discriminatory

18:40.600 --> 18:45.000
currently the standard meaning for this is that you don't discriminate between individuals.

18:45.000 --> 18:48.520
If you have a certain system for working out how much royalties you are going to ask for

18:48.520 --> 18:55.080
you have to apply the same system to each potential licensee. However, maybe we can

18:55.080 --> 18:59.720
expand this, maybe we can work with this term and find a way to talk about non-discriminatory

18:59.720 --> 19:06.280
so that it is not just, so that it prevents the patent regime from discriminating against

19:06.280 --> 19:11.160
free software which cannot pay royalty fees because we cannot count the copies. If that

19:11.160 --> 19:15.720
doesn't work then of course the word fair, it's an even more vague word but maybe we

19:15.720 --> 19:22.800
can do something with this word to just talk about how fair should apply to free software.

19:22.800 --> 19:29.680
There is also as part of this package there is a regulation coming on compulsory licensing

19:29.680 --> 19:33.960
so maybe that angle can also be used there to ask for something that works with free

19:33.960 --> 19:39.440
software so that would have to be a royalty free sub-licensible patent licence with no

19:39.440 --> 19:51.360
domain limit. And the last fix being presented for the first time. So the whole problem with

19:51.360 --> 19:54.680
software patents in Europe has always been that we have a patent law that says software

19:54.680 --> 19:59.680
is not patentable as such and the policy makers, when we complained we don't want software

19:59.680 --> 20:04.440
patents, they said but it's not patentable, look software is not patentable as such. The

20:04.440 --> 20:09.480
problem was that of course the patent applications were always written as patent on a limited

20:09.480 --> 20:13.480
resource device which interacts with this and there is always a way to make software

20:13.480 --> 20:19.760
sound like it's more than just software as such. What if we asked them to give an example?

20:19.760 --> 20:29.320
What if we asked them to put this into a patent law on standard essential patents? Software

20:29.320 --> 20:33.600
which reads, transmits or puts data into a data format standard is an example of software

20:33.600 --> 20:42.760
as such. If we could do this, and this is a crazy idea, maybe we could find a way to

20:42.760 --> 20:48.920
get software as such to be defined in a concrete way and we could actually start using the

20:48.920 --> 20:55.720
idea that software as such is not patentable. Now, when we used to campaign against software

20:55.720 --> 20:59.920
patents, the commission, because this software is not patentable as such language is there,

20:59.920 --> 21:03.160
they said don't worry, there's not going to be American style software patents, it's not

21:03.160 --> 21:08.120
going to happen. I would like to try and find out the documents they used to use and I want

21:08.120 --> 21:12.480
to find any statements, anything that they ever said that explained what their motivation

21:12.480 --> 21:18.880
was, if they were saying that their intention was that data formats for example or compatibility

21:18.880 --> 21:23.560
interoperability, which is a massive buzzword now in the European institutions, if these

21:23.560 --> 21:28.640
things were not meant to be hampered by software patents, then maybe we can say, well, please

21:28.640 --> 21:35.560
clarify this. Your regulation says you want to reduce the unclarity, give us some clarity

21:35.560 --> 21:41.520
on what exactly software as such is and maybe we can put this into law. Those are my five

21:41.520 --> 21:46.040
fixes. I don't have a favourite one, we don't know which one is going to be acceptable,

21:46.040 --> 21:50.880
we don't know what text even we have to insert any of these into, but this is something that

21:50.880 --> 21:57.160
we will be continuing to hold a dialogue on in the coming weeks and months and I hope

21:57.160 --> 22:03.120
this topic gets lots of attention and lots of you get involved. With that, we do have

22:03.120 --> 22:08.320
a tool for coordinating work on this and Panos will brief you.

